{
  "schema_name": "eywa_node_response",
  "schema_version": "v1",
  "orchestration_decision": "delegate",
  "decision_notes": "The problem requires finding a sequence of sibling merges to transform one tree into another. This involves identifying which nodes in the initial tree must be merged to match the structure and parentage of the final tree, while respecting the rule that only siblings can be merged and the larger value is preserved.",
  "helpers": [
    {
      "label": "data_modeling_and_parsing",
      "instructions": "Create a parser to read the number of test cases and the tree structures. Represent the initial tree and the final tree using adjacency lists or parent arrays. Ensure you can easily identify the parent of any node and the set of children for any node in both trees. Store the node values and their relationships clearly."
    },
    {
      "label": "structural_analysis_and_logic",
      "instructions": "Determine the necessary merge operations. For each node in the final tree, identify which nodes in the initial tree correspond to it. Since a merge operation combines siblings and keeps the larger value, a node in the final tree must correspond to the maximum value among a set of siblings in the initial tree. Identify groups of siblings in the initial tree that must be merged to form a single node in the final tree. A merge is valid only if the nodes are siblings and the resulting node's children match the union of the merged nodes' children. Use the property that the final tree is guaranteed to be reachable to identify which initial siblings belong to the same final parent."
    },
    {
      "label": "operation_sequencing",
      "instructions": "Develop a strategy to order the merge operations. Merges must be performed such that we do not attempt to merge nodes that have already been merged or nodes that are no longer siblings. A bottom-up approach (from leaves to root) is generally safer to ensure that when we merge siblings, their children are already correctly structured or will be handled by subsequent merges. Generate a list of pairs (u, v) representing the nodes to be merged."
    }
  ],
  "synthesis_brief": "Combine the outputs by first using the parser to load the trees. Use the structural analysis to identify which groups of siblings in the initial tree must be merged to match the final tree's parent-child relationships. Pass these groups to the sequencing logic to produce a valid list of merge operations. Finally, print the total number of operations followed by each pair of node values to be merged, ensuring the output format strictly follows the problem requirements."
}

